\subsection{1  Introduction}{

\bold{What is Big Data?}

Big data refers to complex and large datasets that need to be processed and analyzed
using some defined tools and analysis techniques to uncover valuable information that
benefits the practitioner.

\bold{Definition 1. (Definition by Gartner)} Big data is high-volume, high-velocity, and/or
high-variety information assets that demand cost-effective, innovative forms of information
processing for enhanced insight and decision making.

\bold{Some properties of big data:}
\itemize{
  \item It refers to a massive amount of data that keeps on growing exponentially with time.
  \item It is so voluminous that it cannot be processed or analyzed using conventional data
    processing techniques.
  \item The term is an all-encompassing one, meaning it includes data, data frameworks,
    the tools and techniques used to process and analyze data.
}

\bold{Types of data}
\itemize{
  \item \bold{Structured data:}
    It refers to highly organized information that can be readily and seamlessly stored
    and accessed from a database by simple search algorithms. That means it can be well
    presented in a table or tabular format where each of the columns or features has a
    well-defined meaning. For e.g., student records stored in a table, UPI transaction
    records of a particular bank, customer, and sales data of a store, etc.

  \item \bold{Unstructured data:}
    Refers to the data having no predefined format or schema, making it difficult to store
    and analyze using traditional database systems, and often requires advanced data
    processing techniques. Examples: Images, audio, and video data, data on customer
    reviews and feedback, data on social media posts and comments, etc.

  \item \bold{Semi-structured data:}
    Semi-structured data does not follow a rigid table structure, but it still contains
    tags, keys, or markers that provide some organization. It lies between structured and
    unstructured data. Examples: Log files generated by servers and applications, XML
    documents, JSON files, etc.
}

\bold{Characteristics of Big Data}

Big Data is commonly explained using the concept of the 5 V's, which describe its main
characteristics and challenges.
\itemize{
  \item \bold{Volume}
    Volume refers to the massive amount of data generated every day from various sources.
    E.g., cell phones, credit card transactions, social media platforms, online transactions,
    satellites, etc.

    Companies of 15 years ago used to handle terabytes of data, whereas data has grown
    to the petabytes. Traditional databases cannot efficiently store or process such large
    datasets, that is why distributed storage systems like Hadoop and cloud platforms are
    used.

  \item \bold{Velocity}
    Velocity refers to the speed at which data is generated and processed. In many
    applications, data is produced continuously and must be analyzed quickly. For example,
    stock market data, online payment systems, and real-time traffic monitoring require
    fast data processing to make immediate decisions.

  \item \bold{Variety}
    Variety refers to the different forms of digitized data. Data may be structured (tables
    in databases), semi-structured (XML, JSON files), or unstructured (text messages,
    images, videos, audio). Handling such diverse data types is one of the major challenges
    in big data analytics.

  \item \bold{Veracity}
    It refers to the quality, reliability, and uncertainty of data. Big data often contains
    noise, missing values, inconsistencies, and biases, making data cleaning and validation
    essential for meaningful analysis.

  \item \bold{Value}
    Refers to the actionable insights and benefits that can be extracted from data. The
    ultimate goal of big data analytics is not just handling large datasets, but transforming
    data into useful information that supports decision-making and innovation. For example,
    businesses use big data to improve customer experience, and enable researchers use it
    to discover new patterns.
}

\bold{Types of Big Data Analytics}

Big Data analytics can be broadly classified into the following four types, based on the
questions they answer and the insights they provide.
\itemize{
  \item \bold{Descriptive Analysis: (What happened in past?)}
    The most commonly used approach to identify current meaning and pattern in the raw
    data. Descriptive analytics focuses on summarizing historical data to understand past
    events and trends. It uses basic statistical measures and visualization techniques to
    present data in a meaningful form.

    Examples -- average marks of students in a semester, website traffic summaries,
    dashboards showing business performance

  \item \bold{Diagnostic Analysis: (Why did it happen?)}
    Diagnostic analytics is used to identify causes and relationships behind observed
    outcomes.

    Examples -- To mathematically detect the reasons for certain behaviors and events
    related to a company, its customers, employees, and products, identifying reasons for
    a drop in sales, etc. Understanding the factors affecting student performance.

  \item \bold{Predictive Analysis: (What is likely to happen in the future?)}
    A method that utilizes statistical and machine learning (ML) algorithms to identify
    trends in the data and make (probabilistic) predictions of future behaviors.

    Examples -- Most of the statistical/ML problems that a data scientist needs to handle,
    such as Stock price prediction, object (image) detection, facial recognition, customer
    churn prediction, weather forecasting, and many more.

  \item \bold{Prescriptive Analysis: (What actions should be taken to make it happen?
    What are its consequences?)}
    It goes beyond predictive analysis and suggests the action benefits from the predictions
    and shows the decision maker the implication of each decision option. It suggests how
    to take advantages of a future or mitigate a future risk.
}

\bold{More Real-Life Examples of the above four types}
\itemize{
  \item \bold{Descriptive Analytics}
  \itemize{
    \item Amazon sales dashboards showing daily and monthly revenue
    \item University result analysis such as pass percentage and grade distribution
    \item Hospital reports on number of patients treated per month
  }
  \item \bold{Diagnostic Analytics}
  \itemize{
    \item Analysis of reasons for customer complaints in the telecoms
    \item Identifying causes of equipment failure in manufacturing industries
    \item Understanding reasons for a drop in website traffic
  }
  \item \bold{Predictive Analytics}
  \itemize{
    \item Demand forecasting for products in e-commerce platforms such as Amazon
    \item Prediction of loan default risk in banking systems
  }
  \item \bold{Prescriptive Analytics}
  \itemize{
    \item Product recommendation systems used by Amazon
    \item Route optimization for delivery and logistics services
    \item Dynamic pricing strategies in airlines and ride-sharing platforms
  }
}
}

