\section{Lecture Notes on Network Science (April 4, 2026)}{

\subsection{1  Introduction}{

A system consisting of many interacting entities is referred to as a \bold{complex system} when
its collective behavior cannot be fully understood merely by analyzing its individual
components in isolation. In such systems, large-scale patterns, structures, and
functionalities emerge from interactions among components. Therefore, to understand
complex systems rigorously, it is essential to study the underlying networks that encode
these interactions.

\bold{Network Science} is the study of such complex systems represented as collections of basic
entities (called nodes) and the relationships or interactions between them (called edges).
More generally, a network may be described as an interconnected or interrelated structure
that provides a mathematical framework for modeling and analyzing complex interactions.
This framework offers a unified formalism to describe systems arising in diverse disciplines,
including physics, sociology, biology, economics, and computer science.
\itemize{
  \item \bold{Social Networks:} A social network consists of individuals connected by relationships
    such as friendship, acquaintance, collaboration, or professional association. Each
    relationship forms a link between two individuals. Examples include online platforms
    such as Facebook and X, job referral networks studied by economists to analyze
    inequality and labor market segregation, and co-authorship networks examined by
    scientists to identify influential researchers and emerging research communities. These
    networks enable the study of human interactions at an unprecedented scale and
    resolution, allowing us to analyze patterns such as who connects with whom, how
    influence spreads, and how information propagates.

  \item \bold{Communication Networks:} Communication networks model the transmission of
    information between entities. In some platforms, such as Facebook and movie
    collaboration networks, links are typically reciprocal. In contrast, in X, connections
    are often directed and non-reciprocal. These structural differences significantly influence
    how ideas, innovations, cultural trends, and misinformation diffuse through populations.

  \item \bold{Transportation Networks:} Transportation networks describe systems that facilitate
    the movement of people and goods.
  \itemize{
    \item Road networks: grid-like structures minimizing geographic distance.
    \item Airline networks (Optimization of capacity and resource consumption under extreme
      reliability requirements)
  }

  \item \bold{Biological Networks:} Biological systems can also be represented as networks,
    including protein-protein interaction networks, gene regulatory networks, metabolic
    networks, etc.
}
}

\subsection{2  Basic Definitions}{
\itemize{
  \item \bold{Network/Graph:} A network can often be represented by a graph. Therefore, we
    often use tools from graph theory to represent and analyze networks. Formally, a graph
    is defined as an ordered pair G = (V, E), where:
  \itemize{
    \item V is a finite non-empty set of elements called vertices or nodes, and
    \item E is a subset of V x V, a set of pairs of vertices called edges or links.
  }
    The number of vertices |V| = N is called the order of the graph, and the number of
    links/edges |E| = L is called its size.

  \item \bold{Nodes/Vertices:} The elements of the set V are called nodes (or vertices). Each
    node represents an entity of the network being studied (e.g., individuals in a social
    network, airports in an airline network, or proteins in a biological network).

  \item \bold{Links/Edges:} The elements of the set E are called links or edges. A link/edge
    represents a relationship or interaction between two nodes/entities of the network. A
    link (i, j) in E joins the nodes i and j, for i, j in V.

  \item \bold{Adjacent nodes:} Two nodes are called adjacent or connected if there is a link
    between them. The connected nodes are called neighbors. So, the set of adjacent
    nodes of a particular node k in V is given by
      {i in V : (i, k) in E and (k, i) in E}.

  \item \bold{Directed and Undirected Networks:} A network in which the links do not have a
    direction and are represented by line segments between pairs of nodes is called an
    undirected network (Example - Facebook). On the other hand, a network in which the
    links are directed and represented by arrows is called a directed network (Example -
    Wikipedia).

    Mathematically, if (i, j) in E => (j, i) in E, the graph is called undirected, and the
    edges can then be represented as unordered pairs {i, j}.

    On the other hand, if (i, j) in E does not necessarily imply (j, i) in E, then the graph
    is called directed.

  \item \bold{Weighted and Unweighted Networks:} A network in which all the links are of the
    same importance is called an unweighted network. On the other hand, a network where
    all the links are not of the same importance is called a weighted network (Example -
    Air transportation networks). In a weighted network, each link is associated with a
    weight, which signifies the importance of the link. In particular, w_{ij} indicates the
    weight of the link connecting nodes i and j.

    Mathematically, a weighted graph is defined by a triplet
      G = (V, E, w),
    where w : E -> R assigns a numerical weight to each edge.

    In weighted networks, the links are depicted by lines of different widths. The widths
    indicate the weight of a link. Thicker the line, higher is the weight associated with
    the link. A link with 0 weight is indicated by the absence of a line.

  \item \bold{Regular Network:} A network in which every node is linked to equal number of
    nodes is called a regular network.

  \item \bold{Some Special Types of networks:}
  \itemize{
    \item \bold{Null network:} A network in which there are no links between the nodes is called a
      null network.
    \item \bold{Bipartite network:} A network which consists of two groups of nodes such that
      links only connect nodes from different groups and not nodes from the same group is
      called a bipartite network. (Example - network of songs and artists, network of
      products and customers etc.)
    \item \bold{Cycle network:} A network with N nodes and N links forming a cycle is called a
      cycle network.
    \item \bold{Star network:} A complete bipartite network in which one group contains only one
      node and the other group contains multiple nodes is called a star graph. All the links
      are connected to a single central node.
  }
}
}

\subsection{3  Some Common Measures}{

Note that, the maximum number of links in a network is bounded by the possible number
of distinct connections among the nodes of the system.

\bold{Complete Network}

A network with the maximum number of links, i.e., a network in which all pairs of nodes
are connected, is called a complete network.

The maximum number of links in an undirected network with N nodes is the number of
distinct pairs of nodes given by

  L_max = C(N, 2) = N(N-1)/2

Similarly, a bipartite network is complete if each node in one group is connected to every
node in the other group. Thus, for a bipartite network, L_max = N_1 x N_2, where N_1
and N_2 are the sizes of the two groups.

\bold{Density}

The proportion of actually existing links to the maximum number of links, i.e., the
proportion of the pairs of nodes that are actually connected in a network is called its
density.

So, the density of a complete network is 1.

The density of a network with N nodes and L links is given by d = L / L_max.

For undirected network: d = 2L / (N(N-1)).

For directed network: d = L / (N(N-1)).

\bold{Sparsity}

In practice, the number of existing links in a given network is much smaller than the
maximum number, as most of the nodes are not connected to each other. Thus, in
practice, the density of a network is much smaller than 1. This feature of a network is
called sparsity. The fewer the edges in a network, the sparser it is. (Example - Facebook
is a sparse network.)

As a network size increases, it is interesting to see how the number of links increase with
respect to the number of nodes. A network is said to be sparse if the number of links
grows at most proportionally to the number of nodes in a linear rate. If instead, the
number of links grows faster (say, quadratically with respect to the number of nodes), we
call the network dense.

\bold{Subnetwork}

A subset of a network which is itself a network is called a subnetwork. A subnetwork is
obtained by selecting a subset of the nodes and considering all the existing links within
these nodes. Some examples of subnetworks are:
\itemize{
  \item \bold{Clique:} A subnetwork which is complete is called a clique.
  \item \bold{Ego network:} A subnetwork consisting of a chosen node and its neighbours is called
    an ego network. (often studied in social networks)
}

\bold{Degree}

The degree of a node in an undirected network is defined as the number of links or
neighbors of the node. A node with no neighbors is called a singleton.

The degree of the i-th node in a network is denoted by k_i. For a singleton, k_i = 0.

The average degree of a network is defined by the means of the degrees of all nodes in a
network. It is denoted by <k>, and is given by

  <k> = (1/N) * sum_{i=1}^{N} k_i

For an undirected network <k> = d(N-1). So, d = <k> / (N-1). N-1 is the maximum
degree of a node in a network. Intuitively, the density is the ratio of the average degree
to the maximum degree.

In an undirected network, the presence of a link between two nodes connects the two
nodes in both directions. In contrast, the presence of a link in a directed network does
not necessarily imply the presence of a link in the opposite direction.

Thus, the degree of a node in a directed network, is studied by considering the incoming
and outgoing links separately.
\itemize{
  \item The number of incoming links, also called predecessors, of a node is called its
    \bold{in-degree} and is denoted by k_i^{in}.
  \item The number of outgoing links, also called successors, of a node is called its
    \bold{out-degree} and is denoted by k_i^{out}.
}

\bold{Strength (Weighted Network)}

For a weighted undirected network, the strength or the weighted degree of a node i,
denoted by s_i, is the sum of the weights of the links that connects it to other nodes. In
particular,

  s_i = sum_{j=1}^{N} w_{ij},

where w_{ij} is the weight of the link between nodes i and j. w_{ij} = 0 implies there is
no link between nodes i and j.

For a weighted directed network, the in-strength and out-strength of the i-th node are
respectively denoted by

  s_i^{in} = sum_{j=1}^{N} w_{ji},
  s_i^{out} = sum_{j=1}^{N} w_{ij}.
}

\subsection{4  Network Representations}{

To store/retrieve a network in/from the computer memory, we need to formally represent
its nodes and links. Some ways to do it are described below.

\bold{Adjacency Matrix}

For a network with N nodes, the adjacency matrix is an N x N matrix where each element
represents the link between the nodes indexed by its row and column. In particular, the
N x N adjacency matrix A = ((a_{ij})) is defined as

  a_{ij} = 1 if nodes i and j are connected,
           0 otherwise.

NOTE:
\itemize{
  \item For \bold{undirected} networks, the adjacency matrix is \bold{symmetric}. For a \bold{directed}
    network, it is a \bold{non-symmetric} matrix.
  \item For an \bold{unweighted} network, the elements of the matrix takes values 1 and 0,
    indicating the presence or absence of a link respectively. For a \bold{weighted} network,
    the matrix takes values equal to the link weights.
}

Advantage: It meets the mathematical formalism of representing networks.

Disadvantage: It is not efficient for storing real networks which are large and sparse. The
required storage space grows like the square of the network size and if the network is
sparse, then most of the spaces are wasted storing zeroes.

\bold{Adjacency List}

It is a data structure that stores the list of neighbors for each node.

Advantage: It is efficient for storing large and sparse networks since non-existing links are
ignored.

Disadvantage: It lacks mathematical formality.

\bold{Edge List}

Stores each link as pair (i, j) or triplet (i, j, w_{ij}).

It lists each link as a pair of connected nodes. We also need to separately list the nodes
for singletons. In case of weighted networks, each link is indicated by a triplet, where the
third element of the triplet indicates the weight of the link.

Advantage: It is efficient for storing large and sparse networks since non-existing links are
ignored.

Disadvantage: It lacks mathematical formality.
}

\subsection{5  Properties of Networks}{

\subsubsection{5.1  Assortativity}{

Assortativity is a structural property of a network that measures the tendency of nodes
to connect with other nodes that are similar in some attribute. For example, in a social
network, people living in the same geographic area, friends having similar hobbies may,
citizens having same political leanings, etc., may have a high tendency to be connected
with each other. Assortativity is found commonly in social networks, however, they may
appear in other networks also. Usually, assortativity in a network is represented by a
color.

A network is said to be \bold{assortative} if nodes preferentially attach to other nodes that
are 'similar' to them. Conversely, it is \bold{disassortative} if nodes tend to connect to nodes
that are not 'similar'. Similarity may be defined in terms of different factors such as, node
degree, a categorical attribute (e.g., gender, profession, community), a numerical variable
(e.g., age, income) etc.

Assortativity based on degree is called \bold{degree assortativity}.
\itemize{
  \item \bold{Assortative networks:} High degree nodes are connected to other high degree nodes
    and low degree nodes are connected to other low degree nodes. Hubs form a densely
    connected core while low degree nodes are loosely attached to each other and/or to
    core nodes. Such networks have a core-periphery structure.

  \item \bold{Disassortative networks:} High degree nodes tend to connect to low degree nodes
    and vice versa. Hubs are formed at the center of star like components. For example,
    Web, food-webs, biological networks etc.
}

\subsubsection{5.1.1  Measures of Assortativity}{

\bold{Assortativity Coefficient:} Pearson product moment correlation coefficient between
degrees of pairs of linked nodes.

\bold{k nearest neighbours:}

The average degree of the neighbours of node i is

  k_{nn}(i) = (1/k_i) * sum_{j=1}^{N} a_{ij} * k_j,

where a_{ij} = 1 if nodes i and j are neighbours, 0 otherwise.

The k nearest neighbour measure for nodes of a given degree k, denoted by <k_{nn}(k)>,
is then defined as the average values of k_{nn}(i) across all nodes of degree k. Thus, if
S_k denotes the set of all nodes of degree k, then <k_{nn}(k)> can be defined as

  <k_{nn}(k)> = (1/|S_k|) * sum_{i in S_k} k_{nn}(i).

If <k_{nn}(k)> is an increasing function of k, then the network is assortative while if
<k_{nn}(k)> is a decreasing function of k, then the network is disassortative.
}
}

\subsubsection{5.2  Paths}{

A path is a way to connect any two nodes in a network. If one can move from a source
node to a target node by traversing a sequence of links in a network, we say there exists
a path between the two nodes. The path is the sequence of links traversed.

The number of links traversed in a path is called its \bold{path length}.

Notes:
\itemize{
  \item There may be multiple paths connecting two nodes.
  \item Different paths may have different lengths and they may or may not share common
    links.
  \item A cycle is a special path that can go from one node back to itself.
}

The natural distance between two nodes is the minimum number of links traversed in a
path connecting the two nodes. Such a path is called the \bold{shortest path} and its length is
called the \bold{shortest path length}. Note that there can be multiple shortest paths between
two nodes.

In a weighted network like a transportation network, a link is often associated with the
geographic distance between two nodes (weights); in such cases, we can define the path
lengths as the sum of the distances associated with links along the path.

Let us denote the shortest path length between nodes i and j as l_{ij}. Then, using the
shortest path lengths as a measure of distance among nodes, we can define --
\itemize{
  \item Average path length of an undirected unweighted network:

      <l> = (1 / C(N,2)) * sum_{1 <= i < j <= n} l_{ij}.

  \item Average path length of a directed unweighted network:

      <l> = (1 / (N(N-1))) * sum_{i != j} l_{ij}.

  \item \bold{Diameter:} The diameter of a network is the maximum shortest path length across all
    pairs of nodes. It is given by

      l_max = max_{i != j} l_{ij}.
}

Sometimes, in calculating the average path length, if for a pairs of nodes, a path is
missing, then the shortest path length between that pair of nodes is taken to be infinity.
In such cases, one can define the average path length as the harmonic mean

  <l> = ( (1/C(N,2)) * sum_{1 <= i < j <= n} (1/l_{ij}) )^{-1}.
}

\subsubsection{5.3  Connectedness}{

Connectedness of a network is the extent to which the nodes are connected to each other.
If in a network, one can reach from any node to any other node by following a path
through links, the network is said to be \bold{connected}.

The higher the density, the greater is the chance that the network is connected.

A network which is not connected is called a \bold{disconnected} network.

A \bold{component} is a subnetwork containing one or more nodes such that there exists a path
between any pairs of these nodes but there are no paths connecting them to other
components.
}

\subsubsection{5.4  Social distance}{

The average path length characterizes how close or far we expect the nodes to be in a
network. To examine the path lengths in different networks is a question extensively
studied.

In transportation networks or power grid networks paths can be long. On the other hand
in social networks, movie-star networks and co-authorship networks, paths are usually of
short length. The path lengths define the concept of social distance.

In classifying networks as long or short, it is important to observe the relationship
between average path length and network size. If the average path length grows
logarithmically with the size of the network, that is, <l> ~ log N, we say that the
average path length of the network is short. This means that the network might have
tens of millions of nodes, yet the average path length can be in single digits. Further, the
network size may get multiplied by many times but the average length would only get
longer by a few steps. Short paths that obey this relationship are usually found in social
networks, collaboration networks and movie-star networks.
}

\subsubsection{5.5  Clustering Coefficient}{

In a social network like Facebook, if Y and Z are friends of X, then there is high chance
that Y and Z are friends to each other. This translates into the presence of many triangles
in a social network. A triangle is a triad of nodes where every pair of nodes are connected.

The \bold{clustering coefficient} of a node is the fraction of the node's neighbours that are
connected to each other. Formally, clustering coefficient of node i is defined as

  C(i) = tau_i / C(k_i, 2),

where tau_i is the number of triangles involving the node i. Note that C(i) is defined
only when k_i > 1.

The clustering coefficient can then be interpreted as the ratio of the number of triangles
that include the node to the total number of triangles that the node could participate in.

The average clustering coefficient of a network is the average of the clustering coefficient
of its nodes, and it is given by

  C = (1 / N_{k>1}) * sum_{i: k_i > 1} C(i),

where N_{k>1} denotes the number of nodes whose degree is more than 1.

Note that this definition of clustering coefficient applies only to undirected networks.

A low average clustering coefficient indicates that the network has low number of
triangles and a high average clustering coefficient indicates that the network has a large
number of triangles. Social networks usually have a high clustering coefficient (> 0.5).
}

\subsubsection{5.6  Heterogeneity}{

Heterogeneous networks play a wide variety in the elements and roles of its nodes. This
reflects the diversity present in the complex systems described by networks. The
importance of a node or link is estimated by computing its centrality. There are several
ways to measure network centrality.

\enumerate{
  \item Degree
  \item Closeness
  \item Betweenness
}

\bold{Degree centrality}

A node is central if it has significantly more degree than others. Now consider a network
with N nodes. Typically, the degree centrality of a node is normalized by dividing it by
the highest value of degree in the observed graph, i.e., N-1.

So, for an undirected network, the normalized degree centrality of a node i is given by

  C_D(i) = k_i / (N-1),

where k_i is the degree of the node i. Again, for a directed network, the in-degree
centrality and out-degree centrality are respectively given by

  C_D^{in}(i)  = k_i^{in}  / (N-1),
  C_D^{out}(i) = k_i^{out} / (N-1),

where k_i^{in} and k_i^{out} are respectively the in-degree and out-degree of the node i.
(These definitions correspond to the unweighted networks. Similarly, formulate the same
for directed networks.)

\bold{Closeness centrality}

Closeness centrality measure captures the interaction between one node and all other
nodes in a network by explaining the relationship between nodes at different depth levels.
The raw closeness centrality of a node i is defined as

  C_c(i) = 1 / sum_{j=1}^{N} d(i,j),

where d(i, j) is the shortest path length between nodes i and j. The normalized closeness
centrality of a node i is defined as

  C_c^{norm}(i) = (N-1) / sum_{j=1}^{N} d(i,j).
}
}
}

