\section{Hadoop MapReduce -- Lecture Note 5}{

Hadoop MapReduce is the \bold{"Processing Unit"} and using this component, we can process
the Big Data stored on Hadoop HDFS. Big Data stored on Hadoop HDFS is not stored
traditionally. The data gets divided into chunks of data stored in respective DataNodes.
So, the entire data is not stored in one centralized location.

Hence a native client application like Java, Python or any such application cannot process
the data in the current format and we need a special framework that can process the
fragmented data blocks stored in respective DataNodes. The processing is done using
Hadoop MapReduce processing.

\subsection{Advantages of MapReduce}{

There are two advantages to this technology.

\bold{1. Parallel Processing}

The very first advantage is parallel processing. Using MapReduce we can always process
the data in parallel.

As per the Master-Slave diagram, there are five Slave Machines (Slave A through Slave E)
and some data are residing on these Machines. Here, the data gets processed parallelly
using Hadoop MapReduce and thus processing becomes fast. What happens is that the
entire chunk of data gets divided by Hadoop HDFS into HDFS Blocks and the MapReduce
processes these chunks of data, making processing fast.

\bold{Architecture (Parallel Processing):}
\preformatted{
              [ Master ]
                  |
    +------+------+------+------+
    |      |      |      |      |
[SlaveA][SlaveB][SlaveC][SlaveD][SlaveE]
}

\bold{2. Data Locality}

This is one versatile thing that is given by Hadoop MapReduce -- we can process the data
where it is. Data that are moved into Hadoop Cluster gets divided into HDFS Blocks and
these Blocks are saved into Slave Machines or DataNodes. The MapReduce sends the
processing and logic to the respective Slave Nodes or DataNodes where the data is
residing as HDFS Blocks. The processing is executed over a smaller chunk of data in
multiple locations in parallel. This saves a lot of time as well as Network Bandwidth that
is required to move Big Data from one location to another.

\bold{Note:} The data we are processing is Big Data broken down into chunks, and if we start
moving the Big Data directly through the allotted Network channels into a centralized
machine and process it, then it will give us no advantage as we are going to consume the
entire Bandwidth in moving the data to a centralized server.

\bold{Benefits:}

Using Hadoop MapReduce we are not just doing \bold{"Parallel Processing"}, we are also
processing the data on to the respective Slave Nodes or DataNodes where the chunks of
data are present, and hence we are also \bold{"Saving a lot of Network Bandwidth"} which is
very beneficial.

Finally, the Slave Machines are done with the processing of data stored at Slave Machines
and they send back the results to the Master Machine -- the results are not as big as the
blocks that were stored on the Slave Machines, so it will not utilize a lot of bandwidth.

The Slave Machines send the result back to the Master Machine, these results are
aggregated together, and the final result is sent back to the Client Machine which
submitted the job.
}

\subsection{Flow of MapReduce}{

\bold{Step-by-step flow:}
\enumerate{
  \item Job Client submits the job to Job Tracker and simultaneously copies the Mapper,
    Reducer, and config package to HDFS.
  \item Job Tracker looks up NameNode to identify the data information.
  \item Job Tracker creates an execution plan and executes TaskTracker. JobTracker also
    coordinates the Task Tracker and maintains the status of TaskTracker.
  \item Task Tracker, which is placed locally to the data node, identifies the available slots
    in the local node; if not available locally, it goes to rack or cross racks. Task Tracker
    reports progress to JobTracker via heartbeats.
  \item Job Tracker first allows executing the entire Mapper task; once all mappers are
    complete, it starts executing the Reducer task. Job Tracker also reschedules the task
    if it fails. Once TaskTracker finishes, it updates the status to Job Tracker.
}

\bold{High-level MapReduce Process Flow (Hadoop Clusters):}
\preformatted{
  +-------------+         +---------------------+         +------------------+
  |  Job Client |         |     Hadoop Clusters  |         |      Output      |
  |-------------|         |---------------------|         |------------------|
  | Submit Job  |---->    |   Job Tracker        |         |  File1           |
  | Program Pkg |         |   (coordinates)      |         |  File2           |
  | (mapper,    |         |       |              |         |  ...             |
  |  reducer,   |         |   Name Node          |         +------------------+
  |  config)    |         |       |              |
  +-------------+         |  Task Trackers       |
         |                |  +----------------+ |
         |                |  | Data Node-1    | |
  Move to HDFS            |  | Mappers -> map | |
         |                |  | Shuffle / Sort | |
         v                |  | Reducers       | |
     [Package]            |  +----------------+ |
         |                |        ...          |
         +--Fetch map      |  +----------------+ |
            reduce pkg --> |  | Data Node-n    | |
                           |  | Mappers -> map | |
                           |  | Shuffle / Sort | |
                           |  | Reducers       | |
                           |  +----------------+ |
                           +---------------------+
}

MapReduce process keeps the TaskTracker locally and executes the job where data reside,
which optimizes the network latency.
}

\subsection{How MapReduce Works -- The Two Phases}{

The MapReduce task is done in two phases:

\bold{Phase overview (data flow):}
\preformatted{
  [HDFS Split]    [HDFS Split]    [HDFS Split]
       |               |               |
     [Map]           [Map]           [Map]
   /      \         /    \          /    \
(key1,v1)(keyk,vk) ...             ...

          |         |         |
          +----+----+----+----+
               |
      [Shuffle & Sort: Aggregate values by key]
               |
     (Key1, intermediate values) ... (Keyk, intermediate values)
               |                              |
           [Reduce]                       [Reduce]
               |                              |
     (Final key1, final value)   (Final keyk, final value)
}

\subsubsection{Phase 1: Map Phase}{

\bold{a. RecordReader}

Hadoop divides the inputs to the MapReduce job into fixed-size splits called \bold{input splits}
or \bold{splits}. The RecordReader transforms these splits into records and parses the data into
records but it does not parse the records itself. RecordReader provides the data to the
mapper function in \bold{key-value pairs}.

\bold{b. Map}

In the map phase, Hadoop creates one map task which runs a user-defined function called
the \bold{map function} for each record in the input split. It generates zero or multiple
intermediate key-value pairs as map task output.

The map task writes its output to the local disk. This intermediate output is then processed
by the reduce tasks which run a user-defined reduce function to produce the final output.
Once the job gets completed, the map output is flushed out.

\bold{c. Combiner}

Input to the single reduce task is the output from all the Mappers -- that is, output from
all map tasks. Hadoop allows the user to define a combiner function that runs on the map
output. Combiner groups the data in the map phase before passing it to the Reducer. It
combines the output of the map function which is then passed as an input to the reduce
function.

\bold{d. Partitioner}

When there are multiple reducers, the map tasks partition their output, each creating one
partition for each reduce task. In each partition, there can be many keys and their
associated values, but the records for any given key are all in a single partition. Hadoop
allows users to control the partitioning by specifying a user-defined partitioning function.
Generally, there is a default Partitioner that buckets the keys using the hash function.
}

\subsubsection{Phase 2: Reduce Phase}{

\bold{a. Sort and Shuffle}

The Reducer task starts with a shuffle and sort step. The main purpose of this phase is to
collect the equivalent keys together. Sort and Shuffle phase downloads the data written by
the partitioner to the node where the Reducer is running.

It sorts each data piece into a large data list. The MapReduce framework performs this
sort and shuffle so that we can iterate over it easily in the reduce task.

The sort and shuffling are performed by the framework automatically. The developer
through the comparator object can have control over how the keys get sorted and grouped.

\bold{b. Reduce}

The Reducer -- which is the user-defined reduce function -- performs once per key
grouping. The reducer filters, aggregates, and combines data in several different ways.
Once the reduce task is completed, it gives zero or more key-value pairs to the
OutputFormat. The reduce task output is stored in Hadoop HDFS.

\bold{c. OutputFormat}

It takes the reducer output and writes it to the HDFS file by RecordWriter. By default,
it separates key and value by a tab and each record by a newline character.
}
}

\subsection{MapReduce Examples (Python using mrjob)}{

\subsubsection{Example 1: Counting Page Visits (Count)}{

\bold{Problem:} Compute the total number of times each page is visited in the year 2014,
from web analytics service logs.

\bold{Input format:} (Date, Time, URL, IP, Visit-Length)

\bold{Approach:}
\itemize{
  \item The mapper function parses each line of the input and emits key-value pairs where
    the \bold{key} is the URL and \bold{value} is '1'.
  \item The reducer receives the list of values grouped by the key and sums them up to
    compute the count.
}

\bold{Python Code (Box 3.1):}
\preformatted{
#Total number of times each page is visited in the year 2014

from mrjob.job import MRJob

class MRmyjob(MRJob):
  def mapper(self, _, line):
    #Split the line with tab separated fields
    data=line.split('\t')

    #Parse line
    date = data[0].strip()
    time = data[1].strip()
    url  = data[2].strip()
    ip   = data[3].strip()

    #Extract year from date
    year=date[0:4]

    #Emit URL and 1 if year is 2014
    if year=='2014':
      yield url, 1

  def reducer(self, key, list_of_values):
    yield key, sum(list_of_values)

if __name__ == '__main__':
  MRmyjob.run()
}

