% =============================================================

\section{Spark Eco-System (Lecture 2)}{

The Spark ecosystem is composed of various components: Spark SQL, Spark Streaming,
MLlib, GraphX, SparkR, and the Core API component.

\bold{Ecosystem Overview (component map):}
\preformatted{
  +------------------+       +-------+
  |   Spark SQL      |       | Scala |
  +------------------+       +-------+
  |  Spark Streaming |       | Java  |
  +------------------+       +-------+
  |     MLlib        |<----->| Spark |<---> Python
  +------------------+       +-------+
  |     GraphX       |       |   R   |
  +------------------+       +-------+
  |     SparkR       |
  +------------------+
}

\subsection{a.  Spark Core}{

Spark Core is the foundation of Spark. It also houses the API that contains the backbone of
Spark -- namely \bold{RDDs (Resilient Distributed Datasets)}. The basic functionality of Spark is
present in Spark Core, including memory management, fault recovery, and interaction with
the storage system. It is in charge of essential I/O functionalities like:
\itemize{
  \item Programming and observing the role of Spark cluster
  \item Task dispatching
  \item Fault recovery
  \item It overcomes the shortcomings of MapReduce by using in-memory computation.
}
}

\subsection{b.  Spark SQL}{

Spark SQL is a distributed framework and a Spark package that allows working with
structured and semi-structured data. It allows querying in SQL and HQL (Hive Query
Language), providing declarative queries with optimized storage running in parallel.

It enables powerful interactive and analytical applications across both streaming and
historical data. SparkSQL allows accessing data from multiple sources like Hive tables,
Parquet, and JSON. It also lets you intermix SQL queries with the programmatic data
manipulations supported by RDDs in Python, Java, and Scala, all within a single
application, thus combining SQL with complex analytics.
}

\subsection{c.  Spark Streaming}{

Spark Streaming enables processing of large streams of data. It makes it easy for the
programmer to move between an application that manipulates data stored in memory, on
disk, and data arriving in real time. \bold{Micro-batching} is used for real-time streaming:
small batches are formed from the live data and then delivered to the Spark batch
processing system for processing.

In short, it provides a data abstraction known as \bold{DStream} (Discretized Stream). It also
provides fault tolerance characteristics.
}

\subsection{d.  MLlib}{

Spark \bold{MLlib} (Machine Learning Library) provides algorithms for machine learning as well
as statistical tasks, including:
\itemize{
  \item Classification
  \item Regression
  \item Linear algebra
  \item Clustering
  \item Collaborative filtering
  \item Supporting functions such as model evaluation and data import
}

MLlib is a scalable learning library focused on high-quality algorithms and high speed. It
also contains some lower-level primitives.
}

\subsection{e.  GraphX}{

GraphX is an API for graphs and graph-parallel execution. It is a network graph analytics
engine and a library for performing graph-parallel computation and graph manipulation. It
has various Spark RDD APIs that help create directed graphs with arbitrary properties
linked to vertices and edges.

Spark GraphX also provides various operators and algorithms to manipulate graphs.
Clustering, classification, traversal, searching, and pathfinding are all possible in GraphX.
}

\subsection{f.  SparkR}{

Released in Apache Spark 1.4, SparkR allows data scientists to analyze large datasets and
interactively run jobs on them from the R shell. The main idea behind SparkR was to
explore different techniques to integrate the usability of R with the scalability of Spark. It
is an R package that provides a lightweight frontend for using Apache Spark from R.
}

\subsection{Limitations of Apache Spark}{
\itemize{
  \item Spark does not have its own file management system, so it needs to integrate with
    Hadoop or another cloud-based data platform.
  \item In-memory capability can become a bottleneck when it comes to cost-efficient
    processing of Big Data.
  \item Memory consumption is very high.
  \item It requires large data to be beneficial.
  \item MLlib lacks a number of available algorithms (e.g., Tanimoto distance).
}
}
}

