%  DOCUMENT 5: APACHE SPARK ARCHITECTURE -- LECTURE 1
% =============================================================

\section{Apache Spark Architecture (Lecture 1)}{

\subsection{Introduction}{

Apache Spark is a robust and versatile unified analytics engine specifically designed for the
efficient processing of large-scale datasets. Its capabilities span:
\itemize{
  \item Batch processing
  \item Real-time streaming
  \item Interactive queries
  \item Advanced machine learning workloads
}

Key characteristics underpinning its effectiveness include:
\itemize{
  \item In-memory computing
  \item A unified analytics framework
  \item Support for diverse programming languages (Scala, Java, Python, R)
  \item A rich set of built-in libraries
  \item Inherent fault tolerance
  \item Lazy evaluation of operations
  \item A sophisticated Directed Acyclic Graph (DAG) execution engine
}

Spark offers a significant performance advantage over traditional Hadoop MapReduce,
particularly in scenarios involving iterative algorithms and interactive data mining. Its
development was motivated by the need to address the inherent inefficiencies in earlier
big data processing frameworks like Hadoop.

The underlying architecture of Apache Spark adopts a \bold{master-slave design}: a central
\bold{Spark Driver} acting as the master node manages the overall execution and distributes
tasks to multiple \bold{Spark Executors} that function as worker nodes. A \bold{Cluster Manager}
allocates the necessary resources across the cluster.

\bold{Architecture overview:}
\preformatted{
  +---------------------+           +---------------------------+
  |   Driver Program    |           |       Worker Node         |
  |---------------------|           |---------------------------|
  |   SparkContext      |<--------->|  Executor  |  Cache       |
  +---------------------+     |    |  Task      |  Task        |
           |                   |    +---------------------------+
           v                   |
  +------------------+         |    +---------------------------+
  |  Cluster Manager |<--------+    |       Worker Node         |
  +------------------+              |---------------------------|
                                    |  Executor  |  Cache       |
                                    |  Task      |  Task        |
                                    +---------------------------+
}
}

\subsection{Core Components of Spark}{

\subsubsection{Spark Driver}{

The \bold{Spark Driver} is the central control point for any Spark application -- analogous to the
main program that orchestrates the entire execution process. Its primary function is to
initiate the \bold{SparkContext}, which acts as the gateway to all Spark functionalities and
establishes the connection to the cluster manager.

\bold{Internal components of the Spark Driver:}
\itemize{
  \item \bold{DAG Scheduler} -- converts the logical execution plan into stages
  \item \bold{Task Scheduler} -- assigns tasks to executors
  \item \bold{Backend Scheduler} -- interfaces with the specific cluster manager
  \item \bold{Block Manager} -- manages data block storage and retrieval
}

\bold{Driver responsibilities:}
\itemize{
  \item Splitting the application logic into individual tasks.
  \item Scheduling tasks on available executors based on data locality and resource
    availability.
  \item Coordinating the overall execution of the entire Spark job.
  \item Maintaining a comprehensive view of the application's state.
  \item Negotiating with the cluster manager to acquire required resources.
  \item Monitoring the progress and status of executing tasks.
  \item Collecting results from executors upon task completion.
  \item Maintaining RDD lineage information for re-computation of lost data partitions.
  \item Retrying failed tasks on different executors.
  \item Supporting checkpointing to recover intermediate data in case of Driver failure.
  \item Executing the main() function of the user's application.
}
}

\subsubsection{Spark Executors}{

\bold{Spark Executors} are the worker processes launched on worker nodes, responsible for
executing individual tasks assigned by the Spark Driver. Their primary functions are to run
computations and store data that the application requires.
\itemize{
  \item Each Spark application is allocated its own dedicated set of executor processes.
  \item The lifespan of executors is directly tied to the duration of the application.
  \item Increasing the number of worker nodes (and hence executors) can significantly
    enhance performance by increasing concurrency.
  \item In Hadoop YARN environments, each executor runs as a YARN container.
  \item Spark supports \bold{dynamic allocation} of executors -- scaling up or down based on
    current workload.
  \item Executors also handle intermediate result storage (in memory or on disk) and
    interact with underlying storage systems.
}
}

\subsubsection{Cluster Manager}{

The \bold{Cluster Manager} oversees and maintains the cluster of machines on which Spark
applications run. It operates with an abstraction of "master" and "worker" nodes. Its core
function is to allocate resources (CPU and memory) across the cluster.

\bold{Spark is agnostic to the cluster manager type. Supported managers:}
\itemize{
  \item \bold{Standalone} -- simple built-in manager included with Spark
  \item \bold{Hadoop YARN} -- resource management layer within the Hadoop ecosystem
  \item \bold{Apache Mesos} -- general-purpose cluster manager
  \item \bold{Kubernetes} -- container orchestration platform
}
}
}

\subsection{Apache Spark Application Execution Flow}{

The execution of an Apache Spark application involves the following well-defined steps:

\bold{Step-by-step execution flow:}
\preformatted{
  [1] Job Submission
       User runs: spark-submit <app> <args> <config>
       |
       v
  [2] Driver Program Launch
       Cluster Manager launches the Driver.
       Driver initializes SparkSession / SparkContext.
       Driver interprets user code -> builds logical DAG.
       |
       v
  [3] Resource Allocation & Executor Launch
       Driver requests CPU cores + memory from Cluster Manager.
       Cluster Manager starts executor processes on worker nodes.
       Executors register with the Driver.
       |
       v
  [4] Logical Execution Plan Creation
       User code -> DAG of transformations and actions.
       Catalyst Optimizer refines the logical plan.
       |
       v
  [5] Physical Execution Plan Creation
       Logical plan -> stages and tasks with dependencies.
       Narrow deps (map, filter): grouped into one stage.
       Wide deps (groupByKey, join): mark stage boundaries (shuffle).
       Tungsten generates efficient bytecode.
       |
       v
  [6] Stage & Task Scheduling
       DAG Scheduler divides DAG into stages.
       Task Scheduler assigns tasks to executors (respecting data locality).
       Default scheduling: FIFO. Optional: Fair Scheduler.
       |
       v
  [7] Task Initialization
       Executor receives serialized task from Driver.
       Executor deserializes and prepares task for execution.
       |
       v
  [8] Data Acquisition
       Task identifies its data partition (from HDFS, S3, or shuffle output).
       Executor reads the partition into memory.
       |
       v
  [9] Task Execution
       Task applies transformations (map, filter, flatMap) and/or
       actions (reduce, count, collect) on the partition.
       |
       v
  [10] Intermediate Data Storage (if applicable)
        If caching/persistence is specified, results stored in memory or disk.
       |
       v
  [11] Shuffle Data Handling (if applicable)
        For groupByKey, reduceByKey, join: task sorts and partitions output.
        Shuffled data stored on local disk; location sent to Driver.
       |
       v
  [12] Task Completion & Result Reporting
        Task reports results to Executor.
        Executor aggregates and reports to Driver.
        Small results sent directly; large results stored on disk
        and retrieved by Driver via Block Manager.
}

\bold{Deployment modes:}
\itemize{
  \item \bold{Cluster mode} -- Driver runs inside an Application Master process on a worker node
    (managed by YARN). Suited for long-running production workloads.
  \item \bold{Client mode} -- Driver runs directly on the client machine that submitted the
    application. Suited for interactive development and debugging.
}
}

\subsection{Cluster Manager Details}{

\subsubsection{Standalone Mode}{

Standalone mode is the simplest cluster manager, included directly within the Apache Spark
distribution. It is most suitable for development, testing, or smaller-scale deployments.

\bold{Key characteristics:}
\itemize{
  \item A Standalone cluster is launched by starting a master server and worker processes
    -- either manually or via provided launch scripts.
  \item For testing, all components can run on a single machine.
  \item The master server outputs a \code{spark://HOST:PORT} URL used by workers to
    register.
  \item A web UI is hosted by default at \code{http://localhost:8080}, showing cluster status,
    connected workers, CPU cores, and memory.
  \item Resource allocation is primarily based on available CPU cores; by default, an
    application requests all available cores in the cluster.
  \item Supports authentication via a shared secret configured on each node.
  \item High availability of the master can be configured using \bold{ZooKeeper} for automatic
    recovery.
  \item Supports both client and cluster deployment modes.
}
}

\subsubsection{Hadoop YARN}{

\bold{Hadoop YARN} (Yet Another Resource Negotiator) is the resource management layer
within the Hadoop ecosystem. A key advantage is its ability to support multiple data
processing frameworks (Spark, MapReduce, Flink) concurrently on the same cluster.

\bold{YARN architecture components:}
\itemize{
  \item \bold{ResourceManager} -- global authority arbitrating resources among all applications.
  \item \bold{NodeManager} -- per-node component launching and monitoring task containers.
  \item \bold{ApplicationMaster} -- per-application component managing its lifecycle on the
    cluster.
}

\bold{Spark on YARN specifics:}
\itemize{
  \item Both Spark Executors and the Application Master run inside YARN containers.
  \item The \code{--master} parameter in \code{spark-submit} is set to \code{yarn}.
  \item The ResourceManager address is automatically obtained from Hadoop configuration.
  \item Requires the \code{HADOOP_CONF_DIR} environment variable to be set.
  \item Supports both client mode (Driver on client machine) and cluster mode (Driver inside
    Application Master on a worker node).
  \item Enables dynamic resource sharing between different frameworks on the same cluster.
  \item Provides sophisticated scheduling capabilities (categorization, isolation, and
    prioritization of workloads) and robust security features including authentication.
}
}

\subsubsection{Apache Mesos}{

Apache Mesos is a general-purpose cluster manager offering dynamic resource sharing and
isolation. It can manage workloads from various sources alongside Spark.

\bold{Key Mesos components:}
\itemize{
  \item \bold{Mesos Masters} -- coordinate the cluster and dispatch tasks.
  \item \bold{Mesos Slaves (Agents)} -- perform actual task execution.
  \item \bold{Frameworks} -- applications (like Spark) that register with the Mesos Master to
    receive resource offers on slave nodes.
}

\bold{Two modes for running Spark on Mesos:}
\itemize{
  \item \bold{Coarse-grained mode} (default): A single Spark executor runs within a Mesos
    executor on each slave. This Spark executor then runs multiple Spark tasks.
  \item \bold{Fine-grained mode} (now deprecated): Each Spark task runs within its own Spark
    executor, within a Mesos executor.
}

\bold{Additional features:}
\itemize{
  \item Supports running Docker containers for containerized Spark deployments.
  \item Capable of scheduling CPU, RAM, disk space, and network ports.
  \item Frameworks can accept or reject offered resources based on their specific needs.
}
}
}

\subsection{Key Architectural Abstractions}{

\subsubsection{Resilient Distributed Datasets (RDDs)}{

The \bold{Resilient Distributed Dataset (RDD)} is the foundational data structure in Apache Spark,
forming the core abstraction upon which higher-level APIs like DataFrames and Datasets
are built.

\bold{Key properties of RDDs:}
\itemize{
  \item \bold{Immutable} -- once created, an RDD's state cannot be changed; any modification
    creates a new RDD.
  \item \bold{Fault-tolerant} -- fault tolerance is achieved by keeping track of \bold{lineage
    information} (the history of transformations) to reconstruct lost partitions.
  \item \bold{Distributed} -- the dataset is divided into logical partitions distributed across
    cluster nodes.
  \item \bold{In-memory} -- data is stored and processed in RAM, significantly speeding up
    processing compared to disk-based systems.
  \item \bold{Lazily evaluated} -- transformations do not execute until an action is called,
    allowing Spark to optimize the execution plan.
  \item \bold{Cacheable} -- RDDs can be persisted in memory or on disk for reuse across
    multiple operations.
}

\bold{Two primary types of RDD operations:}
\itemize{
  \item \bold{Transformations} -- define a new RDD from an existing one (e.g., map, filter,
    reduce). These are lazily evaluated.
  \item \bold{Actions} -- trigger execution of transformations and return a result to the driver
    (e.g., count, collect). These cause the DAG to be evaluated.
}

\bold{Three ways to create an RDD:}
\enumerate{
  \item By parallelizing an existing collection in the driver program.
  \item By referencing a dataset in an external storage system (e.g., HDFS, local file
    system).
  \item By performing transformations on an existing RDD.
}

\bold{Five internal properties of each RDD:}
\enumerate{
  \item A list of partitions.
  \item A function for computing each split.
  \item A list of dependencies on other RDDs.
  \item An optional Partitioner for key-value RDDs.
  \item An optional list of preferred locations to compute each split on.
}
}

\subsubsection{Directed Acyclic Graph (DAG)}{

The \bold{Directed Acyclic Graph (DAG)} is a crucial component of Apache Spark's architecture,
serving as the scheduling layer that implements stage-oriented scheduling. It represents a
logical graph of operations performed on RDDs.

\bold{Key characteristics of the DAG:}
\itemize{
  \item A DAG is constructed by Spark when an action is invoked on an RDD.
  \item It is \bold{acyclic} -- there are no circular dependencies in the execution plan.
  \item The DAG Scheduler splits the DAG into \bold{stages} -- collections of tasks that can be
    executed in parallel.
  \item Stage boundaries are marked by \bold{wide dependencies} (shuffle dependencies), arising
    from transformations like \code{join} and \code{groupBy}.
  \item \bold{Narrow dependencies} (e.g., \code{map}, \code{filter}) allow tasks to be pipelined
    within a single stage without shuffling.
  \item The DAG plays a critical role in \bold{fault tolerance}: lost RDDs can be recomputed
    from their lineage recorded in the DAG.
  \item The structure of the DAG can be visualized through the Spark web UI.
}

\bold{DAG Stage types:}
\itemize{
  \item \bold{ShuffleMapStage} -- performs data transformations before a shuffle. Intermediate
    output is written to disk for the next stage to read.
  \item \bold{ResultStage} -- the final stage that executes the action operation and produces
    the result.
}

\bold{Example stage split (word count):}
\preformatted{
  Stage 0 (ShuffleMapStage)
  --------------------------
  RDD_0 --[flatMap()]--> RDD_1 --[map()]--> RDD_2
                                                 |
                                        [reduceByKey() -- SHUFFLE boundary]
                                                 |
  Stage 1 (ResultStage)
  ----------------------
  RDD_3 (aggregated word counts) --[collect() -- Action]--> Driver
}
}
}

\subsection{Benefits of Apache Spark}{
\enumerate{
  \item \bold{Speed -- Up to 100x Faster Than Hadoop}
    Apache Spark's in-memory computing allows it to process data much faster than
    traditional disk-based systems like Hadoop. This is especially pronounced for iterative
    algorithms and interactive queries.

  \item \bold{High-Level APIs in Java, Scala, Python, and R}
    Spark provides high-level APIs in multiple languages, making it accessible to a wide
    range of developers and allowing them to work in their preferred language.

  \item \bold{Versatility}
    Spark's unified framework supports batch processing, real-time streaming, machine
    learning, and graph processing -- all within a single platform.

  \item \bold{Real-Time Processing}
    With Structured Streaming and legacy Spark Streaming, Spark handles live data
    streams and enables real-time decision-making.

  \item \bold{Scalability and Fault Tolerance}
    Designed for horizontal scalability across a cluster of nodes. Fault tolerance is achieved
    through RDD lineage, enabling data recomputation if partitions are lost.

  \item \bold{Extensive Library Support}
    Built-in libraries include Spark SQL, MLlib, GraphX, and Structured Streaming.
}
}

\subsection{Apache Spark Workloads}{
\enumerate{
  \item \bold{Batch Processing with Spark Core}
    Spark Core is the platform's foundation, managing memory, fault recovery, job
    scheduling, and storage interaction. It provides APIs in Java, Scala, Python, and R.

  \item \bold{Machine Learning with MLlib}
    MLlib offers scalable algorithms for classification, regression, clustering, and pattern
    mining. Models trained in R or Python can be saved and integrated into Java or Scala
    applications.

  \item \bold{Real-Time Processing with Spark Streaming}
    Processes data in mini-batches using Spark Core's scheduling capabilities. The same
    codebase can handle both batch and streaming analytics. Supported data sources
    include Twitter, Kafka, Flume, HDFS, and ZeroMQ.

  \item \bold{Interactive Queries with Spark SQL}
    A distributed query engine supporting low-latency interactive queries -- often up to 100x
    faster than traditional MapReduce. Features a cost-based optimizer, columnar storage,
    and code generation. Supports JDBC, ODBC, JSON, HDFS, Hive, ORC, Parquet,
    Amazon Redshift, Amazon S3, and MongoDB.

  \item \bold{Graph Processing with GraphX}
    Spark's framework for distributed graph computation. Enables ETL operations,
    exploratory analysis, and iterative computations on graph datasets with a flexible API
    and a wide variety of distributed graph algorithms.
}
}

\subsection{How Apache Spark Works -- Jobs, Stages, and Tasks}{

\subsubsection{1.  Job}{

A \bold{Job} in Spark is the highest-level unit of execution, representing a computation triggered
by an \bold{action}. An \bold{action} is an operation that returns a result to the driver or writes data
to external storage (e.g., \code{collect()}, \code{count()}, \code{save()}), marking the end of a
transformation chain. When an action is called, Spark constructs a Job and breaks it down
into smaller units called \bold{Stages}.

\bold{Job encompasses:} all transformations (via Stages) -> final output.
}

\subsubsection{2.  Stage}{

A \bold{Stage} represents a group of operations that can be executed together in parallel. A stage
is defined by the presence of a \bold{shuffle operation} -- any operation that requires data to be
redistributed between partitions (e.g., \code{reduceByKey()}, \code{groupByKey()},
\code{join()}). The execution plan is split into stages at shuffle boundaries.

\bold{Two types of stages:}
\itemize{
  \item \bold{ShuffleMapStage} -- performs necessary data transformations before a shuffle.
  \item \bold{ResultStage} -- executes the action operation and finalizes the result.
}
}

\subsubsection{3.  Task}{

A \bold{Task} is the smallest unit of execution, representing a single operation on one partition
of data. Spark distributes tasks across worker nodes, executing them in parallel. Each task
performs the same computation on a different data partition. The number of tasks in a stage
equals the number of data partitions in that stage.
}

\subsubsection{End-to-End Example: Word Count (PySpark)}{

\bold{Code:}
\preformatted{
from pyspark.sql import SparkSession

spark = SparkSession.builder.getOrCreate()
sc    = spark.sparkContext

# Step 0: Create RDD from a sentence (parallelized into partitions)
rdd_0 = sc.parallelize(["She saw Sharif's shoes on the sofa but was she "
                         "so sure those were Sharif's shoes she saw?"])

# Step 1: Tokenize (flatMap - narrow transformation)
rdd_1 = rdd_0.flatMap(lambda x: x.split())

# Step 2: Create (word, 1) pairs (map - narrow transformation)
rdd_2 = rdd_1.map(lambda x: (x, 1))

# Step 3: Count occurrences (reduceByKey - WIDE transformation, causes shuffle)
rdd_3 = rdd_2.reduceByKey(lambda a, b: a + b)

# Step 4: Persist the RDD in memory for reuse
rdd_3.persist()

# Step 5: Trigger the Spark Job (action)
rdd_3.collect()
}

\bold{Execution breakdown:}
\preformatted{
  ACTION: collect() -> triggers Job creation
  |
  +-- Job
       |
       +-- Stage 0 (ShuffleMapStage)
       |    Operations: flatMap() and map() [no shuffle involved]
       |    Tasks: one task per data partition (e.g., 2 tasks for 2 partitions)
       |      Task 1: processes partition 1 -> applies flatMap() and map()
       |      Task 2: processes partition 2 -> applies flatMap() and map()
       |    Output written to local disk for the shuffle.
       |
       [SHUFFLE BOUNDARY: reduceByKey() redistributes data by key across nodes]
       |
       +-- Stage 1 (ResultStage)
            Operations: reduceByKey() aggregation -> collect()
            Tasks: aggregate word counts per partition after shuffle
            Output: final word count result returned to Driver.
}

\bold{Step 1: Job Creation}

The action \code{collect()} triggers the execution of a \bold{Job}. A Job represents the entire
computation triggered by the \code{collect()} operation. When the driver program encounters
this action, it starts executing the transformations and computes the result in a distributed
manner.

Job: This will include all transformations (like \code{flatMap()}, \code{map()},
\code{reduceByKey()}) and will be divided into multiple Stages if needed. The result of this
job will be returned to the driver after the \code{collect()} operation.

\bold{Step 2: Stage Creation}

Since the \code{reduceByKey()} operation requires a shuffle (because it groups data by key),
Spark divides the Job into multiple Stages. The shuffle happens when data needs to be
exchanged between different nodes in the cluster for grouping by key.
\itemize{
  \item \bold{Stage 0 (ShuffleMapStage):} This stage consists of the transformations that occur
    before the shuffle (i.e., \code{flatMap()} and \code{map()}), where no data shuffling is
    involved. These operations are performed on the data without requiring redistribution.

  \item \bold{Stage 1 (ResultStage):} After the shuffle, Stage 1 is responsible for aggregating
    the values (i.e., applying \code{reduceByKey()}) and computing the final result. This stage
    performs the final aggregation of the word counts and prepares the result for the
    \code{collect()} action.
}

\bold{Step 3: Task Execution}

A Task is the smallest unit of computation that operates on a partition of data. When Spark
processes an RDD, it divides the data into multiple partitions, and each partition is processed
by a separate task.

In the given example, \code{rdd_0} is parallelized using \code{sc.parallelize()}, which splits
the input data into multiple partitions. If the data is split into two partitions, Spark will create
two tasks to process them concurrently:
\itemize{
  \item \bold{Task 1:} Processes the first partition of the data and applies \code{flatMap()} and
    \code{map()} transformations.
  \item \bold{Task 2:} Processes the second partition of the data and applies \code{flatMap()} and
    \code{map()} transformations.
}

After the shuffle operation in Stage 1, the tasks will process the data and aggregate the word
counts.

Thus, each partition will be processed by a separate task, and Spark will run these tasks in
parallel across available cores.

\bold{Key takeaways:}
\itemize{
  \item Narrow transformations (\code{flatMap}, \code{map}) are grouped into Stage 0 and run
    within each partition without any data movement across the network.
  \item The wide transformation \code{reduceByKey} requires a \bold{shuffle} -- it redistributes
    data across nodes so that all values for a given key land on the same executor.
    This shuffle marks the boundary between Stage 0 and Stage 1.
  \item Each partition is processed by a separate task, and Spark will run these tasks in
    parallel across available cores.
  \item Calling \code{persist()} on \code{rdd_3} means that if \code{collect()} or any future
    action re-uses \code{rdd_3}, Spark will serve it from memory rather than recomputing
    it from scratch.
}
}
}

\subsection{Scheduling in Spark}{

Apache Spark employs a sophisticated multi-layer scheduling mechanism.

\subsubsection{DAG Scheduler}{

The \bold{DAG Scheduler} orchestrates job execution by implementing stage-oriented scheduling.
It takes the logical execution plan (RDD lineage) and transforms it into a physical plan of
stages, then submits these stages as \bold{TaskSets} to the Task Scheduler.

\bold{Responsibilities:}
\itemize{
  \item Dividing the DAG of RDD operations into a sequence of stages.
  \item Determining preferred task locations based on \bold{data locality}.
  \item Handling failures due to lost shuffle output files by resubmitting affected stages.
  \item Executing stages in topological order to respect dependencies.
  \item Tracking which RDDs are currently cached to avoid redundant computations.
  \item Using an internal event queue architecture for scheduling events.
}
}

\subsubsection{Task Scheduler}{

The \bold{Task Scheduler} schedules individual tasks for execution within a single Spark
application. It receives \bold{TaskSets} from the DAG Scheduler (each TaskSet corresponding
to a stage) and dispatches tasks to worker nodes.

\bold{Responsibilities:}
\itemize{
  \item Dispatching tasks to worker nodes for execution.
  \item Managing task execution and handling retries for failed tasks.
  \item Mitigating the impact of straggler tasks.
  \item Reporting task status and outcomes back to the DAG Scheduler.
  \item Interacting with the cluster manager to launch tasks on available resources.
  \item Calculating the default level of parallelism based on cluster configuration.
  \item Managing heartbeats from executors and handling executor loss events.
}
}

\subsubsection{Backend Scheduler}{

The \bold{Backend Scheduler} is a pluggable abstraction layer that hides the specifics of how
different cluster managers handle task scheduling and resource offers. It allows the rest of
Spark's scheduling logic to remain largely independent of the deployment environment.

\bold{Implementations:}
\itemize{
  \item \bold{Local Backend} -- used when Spark runs in local mode.
  \item \bold{Coarse-Grained Scheduler Backend} -- general implementation for Standalone,
    YARN, Kubernetes, and Mesos (coarse-grained mode).
  \item \bold{Kubernetes Cluster Scheduler Backend} -- for Spark on Kubernetes.
  \item \bold{YARN Scheduler Backend} -- for Spark on YARN.
  \item \bold{Standalone Scheduler Backend} -- for Spark Standalone mode.
  \item \bold{Mesos Fine-Grained Scheduler Backend} -- for fine-grained Mesos mode
    (now deprecated).
}
}

\subsubsection{Scheduling Modes Within an Application}{

When multiple jobs are submitted concurrently within a single Spark application (e.g.,
serving requests from multiple users or threads), Spark provides two scheduling modes:
\itemize{
  \item \bold{FIFO (First-In, First-Out)} -- the default mode. Jobs execute sequentially in the
    order submitted to SparkContext.
  \item \bold{Fair Scheduler} -- enabled by setting \code{spark.scheduler.mode} to
    \code{FAIR}. Provides equal resource sharing among all running jobs over time,
    preventing a single long-running job from monopolizing resources. Also supports
    job priorities for more important jobs to receive a larger fraction of resources.
}
}

\subsubsection{Dynamic Resource Allocation}{

Apache Spark's \bold{Dynamic Resource Allocation} feature allows an application to
automatically adjust the number of executors it uses based on the current workload.
\itemize{
  \item Resources are returned to the cluster when no longer actively used.
  \item Additional executors are requested when pending tasks exceed the capacity of the
    current executor pool.
  \item Requests for new executors happen in rounds, triggered after a configured period
    of backlog.
  \item In Kubernetes environments, this feature dynamically scales executor pods up or
    down.
}
}
}

\subsection{Storage Management}{

\subsubsection{Block Manager}{

The \bold{Block Manager} is a fundamental component managing the storage of \bold{data blocks}
(the basic units of data in Spark) in both memory and on disk. A Block Manager instance
runs within every Spark Driver and every Spark Executor process.

\bold{Key features:}
\itemize{
  \item Provides an interface for uploading and fetching data blocks both locally and
    remotely across various storage types: memory, disk, and off-heap storage.
  \item Calculates the maximum amount of memory available for storage on initialization.
  \item Registers a \code{BlockManagerSlaveEndpoint} for handling block transfer communication.
  \item Uses a \bold{MemoryStore} for blocks stored in memory and a \bold{DiskStore} for
    blocks persisted on disk.
  \item Manages a \bold{Shuffle Client} for reading shuffle data from other executors.
  \item Each node's Block Manager registers itself with the \bold{Block Manager Master} on the
    driver node.
  \item Manages block eviction from memory using strategies like \bold{Least Recently Used
    (LRU)} when space is needed for new data.
}
}

\subsubsection{Data Locality}{

\bold{Data locality} is a critical concept in distributed computing -- the fundamental idea is to
perform computations as close as possible to where the data resides, minimizing costly
network data transfers.

\bold{Data locality levels in Spark} (highest to lowest priority):
\itemize{
  \item \bold{PROCESS_LOCAL} -- data is already in the same JVM as the running code (i.e.,
    in the memory of the executor on the same node). Highest locality.
  \item \bold{NODE_LOCAL} -- data is on the same physical machine as the executor but in a
    different process (e.g., another executor's memory or local disk).
  \item \bold{RACK_LOCAL} -- data is on a different node within the same rack in the data
    center.
  \item \bold{NO_PREF} -- no preference for where the data is accessed from.
  \item \bold{ANY} -- data is located elsewhere on the network, potentially in a different rack.
    Lowest locality.
}

Spark's goal is to schedule tasks at the highest possible locality level to minimize data
transfer and improve overall application performance. The locality level achieved for each
task is an important indicator of job efficiency.
}
}

\subsection{Optimization Techniques}{

\subsubsection{DAG Optimization}{
\itemize{
  \item \bold{Pipelining} -- narrow transformations (no shuffling) are grouped into a single
    stage, allowing multiple operations to be performed in memory on each partition.
  \item \bold{Task reordering} -- filtering operations are performed as early as possible to
    reduce the data volume for subsequent transformations.
  \item \bold{Pruning} -- unnecessary operations are removed if their output is not required for
    the final result.
  \item \bold{Operator combining} -- certain operators are merged to reduce the number of
    steps in the execution plan.
  \item \bold{Broadcast joins} -- for smaller datasets in join operations, Spark can broadcast
    the smaller dataset to avoid large shuffles.
  \item \bold{Catalyst Optimizer} -- when using DataFrames and Datasets, the Catalyst
    Optimizer automatically applies optimization rules to logical and physical plans.
}
}

\subsubsection{Data Partitioning}{
\itemize{
  \item By dividing data into smaller partitions, Spark can distribute processing across
    available executors for parallel execution.
  \item \code{spark.sql.files.maxPartitionBytes} controls the maximum partition size when
    reading from files.
  \item \code{coalesce()} and \code{repartition()} can be used to adjust the number of
    partitions after creation.
  \item General guideline: number of partitions >= total CPU cores in the cluster.
}
}

\subsubsection{Minimizing Shuffle Operations}{

Shuffle operations -- redistributing data across the network between executors -- are
expensive due to network I/O and disk I/O. Minimizing shuffles is a key optimization goal.
\itemize{
  \item Carefully order transformations to reduce the need for data redistribution.
  \item Use broadcast joins for smaller datasets to avoid shuffles altogether.
  \item Tune the number of shuffle partitions using \code{spark.sql.shuffle.partitions}.
}
}

\subsubsection{Caching and Persistence}{

Spark's ability to cache intermediate results using \code{cache()} or \code{persist()} can
significantly reduce computation time for data accessed multiple times.
\itemize{
  \item \bold{MEMORY_ONLY} -- stores RDD as deserialized Java objects in memory.
  \item \bold{MEMORY_AND_DISK} -- stores in memory; spills to disk if memory is insufficient.
  \item Choose the appropriate storage level based on dataset size and available memory.
}
}

\subsubsection{Broadcast Variables}{

When joining a large dataset with a smaller one, broadcasting the smaller dataset to all
worker nodes gives each executor a local copy, eliminating the need to shuffle the smaller
dataset across the network during the join.
}

\subsubsection{DataFrames and Datasets vs. RDDs}{

For structured and semi-structured data, using higher-level APIs (DataFrames and
Datasets) is generally recommended over using RDDs directly. These APIs benefit from
automatic optimizations by the \bold{Catalyst Optimizer}, often resulting in more efficient
execution plans without manual tuning.
}

\subsubsection{Avoiding User-Defined Functions (UDFs)}{

While UDFs provide flexibility, they can be performance bottlenecks -- especially Python
UDFs in a Scala/Java Spark application, due to serialization/deserialization overhead
between the JVM and Python interpreter. Recommendations:
\itemize{
  \item Prefer Spark's built-in functions where possible (they are optimized for performance).
  \item If UDFs are necessary, use \bold{Pandas UDFs} (Vectorized UDFs) which operate on
    batches of data rather than single rows.
}
}

\subsubsection{Memory Management}{

Proper memory configuration is crucial for Spark performance. Key settings:
\itemize{
  \item \code{spark.executor.memory} -- memory allocated to each executor.
  \item \code{spark.driver.memory} -- memory allocated to the driver.
  \item \code{spark.shuffle.memoryFraction} -- memory fraction used for shuffle operations.
}
These should be tuned based on the specific workload and available cluster resources.
}
}
}

