% =============================================================

\section{HDFS Architecture (Lecture Note 4)}{

\subsection{Introduction to HDFS}{

\bold{HDFS (Hadoop Distributed File System)} is a Java-based distributed file system that
allows you to store large data across multiple nodes in a Hadoop cluster. When you
install Hadoop, you get HDFS as the underlying storage system for storing data in a
distributed environment.

\bold{Key characteristics:}
\itemize{
  \item Developed using distributed file system design; runs on commodity hardware.
  \item Unlike other distributed systems, HDFS is highly fault tolerant and designed using
    low-cost hardware.
  \item Holds very large amounts of data and provides easier access. Files are stored
    across multiple machines in a redundant fashion to protect against data loss in case
    of failure.
  \item Makes applications available to parallel processing.
  \item Runs on top of existing file systems on each node in a Hadoop cluster.
  \item A \bold{block-structured} file system -- each file is divided into blocks of a pre-determined
    size, stored across a cluster of one or several machines.
}

\bold{Features of HDFS:}
\itemize{
  \item Suitable for distributed storage and processing.
  \item Hadoop provides a command interface to interact with HDFS.
  \item Built-in servers of NameNode and DataNode help users easily check cluster status.
  \item Streaming access to file system data.
  \item HDFS provides file permissions and authentication.
}
}

\subsection{Basic Terminology}{

\bold{Node:} A node is simply a computer. This is typically non-enterprise, commodity hardware
for nodes that contain data.

\bold{Rack:} A collection of nodes is called a rack. A rack is a collection of 30 or 40 nodes that
are physically stored close together and are all connected to the same network switch.
Network bandwidth between any two nodes in the same rack is greater than bandwidth
between two nodes on different racks.

\bold{Cluster:} A Hadoop Cluster (or just cluster) is a collection of racks.

\bold{Hadoop Cluster topology:}
\preformatted{
                        [ World ]
                           |
               +-----------+-----------+
           [switch]                 [switch]
              |                        |
    +---------+--------+    +----------+---------+
    |         |        |    |          |         |
 [switch]  [switch] [switch] [switch]          [switch]
    |         |        |       |                  |
 NameNode  JobTracker  SecNN  Client           DN+TT (x6)
 DN+TT(x4) DN+TT(x4) DN+TT(x4) DN+TT(x4)
  Rack 1    Rack 2    Rack 3   Rack 4           Rack N
}
(DN = DataNode, TT = TaskTracker, SecNN = Secondary NameNode)
}

\subsection{File Blocks}{

Blocks are the smallest continuous location on a hard drive where data is stored. In any
file system, data is stored as a collection of blocks. Similarly, HDFS stores each file as
blocks scattered throughout the Apache Hadoop cluster.
\itemize{
  \item The default block size is \bold{128 MB} in Apache Hadoop 2.x (64 MB in Apache Hadoop
    1.x), configurable as per requirement.
  \item All blocks of a file are the same size \bold{except the last block}, which can be the same
    size or smaller.
  \item The Hadoop application is responsible for distributing data blocks across multiple
    nodes.
}

\bold{Example -- file block splitting:}
\preformatted{
  File: example.txt  (514 MB total)
  Default block size: 128 MB

  +--------+--------+--------+--------+------+
  |  a     |  b     |  c     |  d     |  e   |
  | 128 MB | 128 MB | 128 MB | 128 MB |  2 MB|
  +--------+--------+--------+--------+------+
  Block 1  Block 2  Block 3  Block 4  Block 5

  Result: 5 blocks created.
  First 4 blocks = 128 MB each.
  Last block (e) = 2 MB only.
}
}

\subsection{Components of HDFS}{

HDFS follows a \bold{Master/Slave Architecture}: a cluster comprises of a single
\bold{NameNode (Master node)} and all other nodes are \bold{DataNodes (Slave nodes)}.
HDFS can be deployed on any machines supporting Java. Though one can run several
DataNodes on a single machine, in practice, DataNodes are spread across various
machines.

\bold{HDFS Architecture overview:}
\preformatted{
  Client                          Metadata
  |                               Name = /home/foo/data
  |--[Metadata ops]-->  NameNode  Replicas = 3
  |                     |         Name = /home/foo/data1
  |                     |         Replicas = 3
  |                  [Block ops]
  |                     |
  |          +----------+----------+
  |          v                     v
  |      DataNodes (Rack 1)    DataNodes (Rack 2)
  |      [  ] [  ] [  ]  <--Replication-->  [ ] [ ] [Blocks]
  |
  |--[Read]-->  DataNodes (Rack 1)
  |
  [Write]--> DataNodes (Rack 1)
}

\subsubsection{NameNode}{

NameNode is the \bold{master node} in the Apache Hadoop HDFS Architecture. It maintains
and manages the blocks present on the DataNodes (slave nodes). NameNode is a highly
available server that manages the File System Namespace and controls client access to
files.

\bold{Important:} User data never resides on the NameNode. The NameNode contains only
\bold{metadata}; actual data resides on DataNodes only.

\bold{Functions of NameNode:}
\itemize{
  \item It is the master daemon that maintains and manages the DataNodes (slave nodes).
  \item Manages the file system namespace.
  \item Records the metadata of all files stored in the cluster, e.g. location of blocks,
    file sizes, permissions, hierarchy, etc. Two files are associated with the metadata:
  \itemize{
    \item \bold{FsImage} -- contains the complete state of the file system namespace since the
      start of the NameNode.
    \item \bold{EditLogs} -- contains all recent modifications made to the file system with
      respect to the most recent FsImage.
  }
  \item Records each change that takes place to the file system metadata. For example,
    if a file is deleted in HDFS, the NameNode immediately records this in the EditLog.
  \item Regularly receives a \bold{Heartbeat} and a \bold{block report} from all DataNodes in the
    cluster to ensure that DataNodes are live.
  \item Keeps a record of all blocks in HDFS and in which nodes these blocks are located.
  \item Responsible for maintaining the replication factor of all blocks.
  \item In case of DataNode failure, the NameNode chooses new DataNodes for new
    replicas, balances disk usage, and manages communication traffic to the DataNodes.
}
}

\subsubsection{DataNode}{

DataNodes are the \bold{slave nodes} in HDFS. Unlike NameNode, DataNode is commodity
hardware -- a non-expensive system which is not of high quality or high-availability. The
DataNode is a block server that stores data in the local file system (ext3 or ext4).

\bold{Functions of DataNode:}
\itemize{
  \item The actual data is stored on DataNodes.
  \item DataNodes perform read-write operations on the file systems as per client request.
  \item They perform operations such as block creation, deletion, and replication according
    to the instructions of the NameNode.
  \item They send heartbeats to the NameNode periodically to report the overall health of
    HDFS; by default, this frequency is set to 3 seconds.
}

\bold{NameNode vs. DataNode -- comparison:}
\preformatted{
  +-----------------------------+-------------------------------+
  |        NAMENODE             |          DATANODE             |
  +-----------------------------+-------------------------------+
  | Controller and manager      | A node other than the         |
  | of HDFS                     | NameNode in HDFS, controlled  |
  |                             | by the NameNode               |
  +-----------------------------+-------------------------------+
  | Also known as master node   | Also known as slave node      |
  +-----------------------------+-------------------------------+
  | Handles the metadata of     | Stores and retrieves blocks   |
  | all files in HDFS and       | according to the master       |
  | controls the DataNodes      | node's instructions           |
  +-----------------------------+-------------------------------+
}
}

\subsubsection{Secondary NameNode}{

The Secondary NameNode is a separate physical machine that acts as a \bold{helper daemon}
of the NameNode. It performs periodic checkpoints, communicates with the NameNode,
and takes snapshots of metadata to minimize downtime and data loss. It works
concurrently with the primary NameNode.

\bold{Secondary NameNode checkpoint flow:}
\preformatted{
  Secondary NameNode                          NameNode
  +--------------------+                   +-----------+
  |                    |--Query EditLogs-->|           |
  |                    |   (regular        |           |
  |                    |    intervals)     |           |
  |  Update FsImage    |                   |  FsImage  |
  |  with EditLogs     |                   |           |
  |                    |                   |           |
  |     FsImage        |<--Copy updated----|  FsImage  |
  |                    |    FsImage back   |           |
  +--------------------+                   +-----------+
}

\bold{Functions of Secondary NameNode:}
\itemize{
  \item Constantly reads all file systems and metadata from the RAM of the NameNode
    and writes it into the hard disk or the file system.
  \item Responsible for combining the EditLogs with FsImage from the NameNode.
  \item Downloads the EditLogs from the NameNode at regular intervals and applies them
    to FsImage. The new FsImage is copied back to the NameNode and is used whenever
    the NameNode is started the next time.
  \item Performs regular checkpoints in HDFS -- therefore it is also called
    \bold{CheckpointNode}.
}
}
}

\subsection{Storing Data into HDFS}{

HDFS stores data in a reliable fashion using \bold{replication and distribution}. Here is the
series of steps that happen when a client writes a file in HDFS:

\bold{Write flow (step-by-step):}
\preformatted{
  [1] Client requests NameNode to create the file, passing file size as parameter.
       |
       v
  [2] NameNode responds with locations of nodes where client can store data.
       By default: 3 locations per block.
       Example: 200 MB file -> 2 blocks (Block 1: 128 MB, Block 2: 72 MB).
       |
       v
  [3] Client starts writing data directly to the first DataNode (of the 3 given).
       Note: If there are 2 blocks, client can start writing them in PARALLEL.
       |
       v
  [4] First DataNode stores the block and replies SUCCESS to client.
       First DataNode then passes the same block to the 2nd DataNode.
       2nd DataNode writes the block and passes it on to 3rd DataNode.
       |
       v
  [5] Result:
       Writing from client to DataNodes: PARALLEL
       Replication between DataNodes:    SERIES
}

\bold{Block placement rules:}
\itemize{
  \item Blocks of the same file can go to different nodes.
  \item Replicated blocks are always on different nodes.
  \item The \bold{first block} is always on the DataNode nearest to the client.
  \item The \bold{2nd and 3rd blocks} are stored based on free capacity of DataNodes and/or
    rack awareness.
}
}

\subsection{Replication Management}{

HDFS performs replication to provide \bold{fault tolerance} and improve \bold{data reliability}.
\itemize{
  \item Data can be lost in many ways: node is down, node lost network connectivity, a
    node is physically damaged, or a node is intentionally made unavailable for
    horizontal scaling.
  \item Without replication, data would be unavailable in any of these situations.
  \item HDFS usually maintains \bold{3 copies} of each Data Block on different nodes and
    different racks. This ensures data availability even if one system is down.
  \item Replication reduces downtime, improves reliability, and makes HDFS fault tolerant.
  \item If one copy is not accessible or is corrupted, data can be read from another copy.
  \item The number of copies of each block is called the \bold{replication factor}. The
    \bold{default replication factor is 3}, which is configurable.
  \item Storage cost of replication: A 128 MB file with replication factor 3 occupies
    \bold{384 MB} (3 x 128 MB) of storage.
}

\bold{Block replication example (5 blocks, 4 nodes, replication factor = 3):}
\preformatted{
          Node 1           Node 2
       +----------+     +----------+
       | Block 1  |     | Block 1  |
       | Block 3  |     | Block 2  |
       | Block 4  |     | Block 4  |
       | Block 5  |     | Block 5  |
       +----------+     +----------+

          Node 3           Node 4
       +----------+     +----------+
       | Block 2  |     | Block 1  |
       | Block 3  |     | Block 2  |
       | Block 4  |     | Block 3  |
       +----------+     | Block 5  |
                        +----------+
  Each block appears on 3 different nodes.
}
}

\subsection{Rack Awareness in HDFS Architecture}{

\bold{Rack:} A collection of around 30-40 machines, all connected using the same network
switch. If that network switch goes down, all machines in that rack will be out of service
(i.e., the rack is down).

\bold{Rack Awareness} was introduced by Apache Hadoop to overcome this issue. It is the
knowledge of how DataNodes are distributed across the racks of a Hadoop cluster.

\bold{How it works:}
\itemize{
  \item In a large Hadoop cluster, to improve network traffic while reading/writing HDFS
    files, the NameNode chooses a DataNode closer to the same rack or a nearby rack
    for read/write requests.
  \item The NameNode achieves rack information by maintaining the rack IDs of each
    DataNode.
  \item NameNode ensures that all replicas are \bold{not} stored on the same rack or on a
    single rack -- it follows the \bold{Rack Awareness Algorithm} to reduce latency and
    improve fault tolerance.
}

\bold{Replica placement with default replication factor of 3:}
\enumerate{
  \item The \bold{first replica} is written to the DataNode creating the file, to improve write
    performance (write affinity).
  \item The \bold{second replica} is written to another DataNode \bold{within the same rack}, to
    minimize cross-rack network traffic.
  \item The \bold{third replica} is written to a DataNode \bold{in a different rack}, ensuring that
    even if a switch or rack fails, the data is not lost.
}

This configuration ensures the file is never lost in case of a Node Failure or even an
entire Rack Failure.

\bold{Replication and Rack Awareness layout (3 racks, 9 nodes):}
\preformatted{
                        [ Switch ]
                 +----------+----------+
                 |          |          |
             [Switch]   [Switch]   [Switch]
              Rack 1     Rack 2     Rack 3
            +--------+ +--------+ +--------+
            |DN 1 A,C| |DN 4 A  | |DN 7 B  |
            |DN 2 C,A| |DN 5 B  | |DN 8    |
            |DN 3    | |DN 6 B  | |DN 9 C  |
            +--------+ +--------+ +--------+

  Block A replicas: DN1 (Rack1), DN2 (Rack1), DN4 (Rack2)
  Block B replicas: DN5 (Rack2), DN6 (Rack2), DN7 (Rack3)
  Block C replicas: DN1 (Rack1), DN2 (Rack1), DN9 (Rack3)

  Block replica placement rule:
    - One replica on local node
    - Second replica on a remote rack
    - Third replica on the same remote rack
    - Additional replicas are randomly placed
}

\bold{Advantages of Rack Awareness:}
\itemize{
  \item \bold{Minimize writing cost and maximize read speed} -- Rack awareness places
    read/write requests to replicas on the same or nearby rack, minimizing writing cost
    and maximizing reading speed.
  \item \bold{Maximize network bandwidth and low latency} -- Rack awareness maximizes
    network bandwidth by block transfers within a rack. This is particularly beneficial
    when tasks cannot be assigned to nodes where their data is stored locally.
  \item \bold{Data protection against rack failure} -- By default, the NameNode assigns the
    2nd and 3rd replicas of a block to nodes in a rack different from the first replica,
    providing data protection even against rack failure.
}
}

\subsection{MapReduce (HDFS Context)}{

MapReduce is a programming framework that allows parallel and distributed processing
on huge datasets in a distributed environment.

\bold{MapReduce components:}
\preformatted{
  MapReduce
  |
  +-- 1. Architectural Components
  |       a) Job Tracker
  |       b) Task Trackers
  |
  +-- 2. Functional Components
          a) Mapper (map)
          b) Combiner (Shuffler)
          c) Reducer (reduce)
}

\subsubsection{Architectural Components}{

The complete execution process (execution of Map and Reduce tasks) is controlled by
two types of entities:
\itemize{
  \item \bold{Job Tracker} -- acts like a master; responsible for the complete execution of the
    submitted job. Resides on the \bold{NameNode}.
  \item \bold{Task Trackers} -- act like slaves; each performs part of the job. Reside on
    \bold{DataNodes}.
}

For every job submitted for execution, there is one Job Tracker and multiple Task
Trackers.

\bold{Job Tracker and Task Tracker coordination (3 Task Trackers on 3 DataNodes):}
\preformatted{
                     Job Tracker On NameNode
                            |
  Client 1 --[Submit Job]--> Job Tracker <--[Status Update]-- Task Tracker 1
                            |                                   | Map Task | Reduce Task
                            |            <--[Status Update]-- Task Tracker 2
                            |                                   | Map Task | Reduce Task
                            |            <--[Status Update]-- Task Tracker 3
                                                                | Map Task | Reduce Task
}

\bold{Responsibilities and interactions:}
\itemize{
  \item A job is divided into multiple tasks which are then run on multiple DataNodes in a
    cluster.
  \item It is the responsibility of the Job Tracker to coordinate the activity by scheduling
    tasks to run on different DataNodes.
  \item Execution of individual tasks is handled by the Task Tracker, which resides on
    every DataNode executing part of the job.
  \item The Task Tracker's responsibility is to send a progress report to the Job Tracker.
  \item In addition, the Task Tracker periodically sends a \bold{'heartbeat'} signal to the Job
    Tracker to notify it of the current state of the system.
  \item The Job Tracker keeps track of the overall progress of each job.
  \item In the event of task failure, the Job Tracker can reschedule it on a different Task
    Tracker.
}
}
}
}

